675","1573–Male":"1573–Deceased","1573–Female":"1573–Deceased","before 1630":"before 1630","1660":"about 1660","1682":"1682","1593":"about 1593","1590":"1590","1610":"1610","1598":"1598","1675":"1675","1630":"about 1630","1663":"1663","environ 1619":"about 1619","1573":"1573","1619":"1619","1618":"1618","1648":"1648","Urmatt, France":"Urmatt, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France":"Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France","Abreschviller, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France","Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Abreschviller, Moselle, Lorraine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tarillon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcide, Normand, Aime, Alphonse, Colette, Napoleon, Pierre, Raoul, Sebastien.","French: topographic name from a diminutive of Old French <i>taillis</i> ‘copse, wood where it is allowed to cut trees’, a derivative of the verb <i>taillier</i> ‘to cut’. Compare   Lataille   1 and   Tyo  .","History: The progenitor of the American Taillons was Olivier Michel <i>dit</i> Le Tardif and Taillon from La Rochelle in Charente-Maritime, France, who married Marie-Madeleine Cauchon in Château-Richer, QC, in 1671. The first secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name was the surname of his stepfather, while the second one was his own choice. His descendants also bear the surnames <i>Lataille</i> (originally used as a <i>dit</i> name, too) and <i>Tyo</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Tyo","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Taillon  .","History: This surname is borne by the descendants of Olivier Michel <i>dit</i> Le Tardif and Taillon from France (see   Taillon  )."]},{"name":"Lataille","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Aime, Aldor, Armand, Emile, Solange.","Altered form of French   Taillon  , a cognate of 2 below.","French: habitational name from any of several places called La Taille, or a topographic name from a derivative of the verb <i>taillier</i> ‘to cut’, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>, denoting a wood where it is allowed to cut trees. This surname is very rare in France."]}]},{"name":"Antoinette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine diminutive of   Antoine  , which has become popular in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1670184,"age":5,"year":"1598","julianDay":2304718,"title":"Edict of Nantes ","description":"Under the rule of Henry IV of France the Edict of Nantes was issued giving the people some religious liberty. The edict brought an end to the religious wars that were going on at the time. ","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Edict-of-Nantes","urlTitle":"Encyclopedia Britannica- Edict of Nantes","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1355839,"age":17,"year":"1610","julianDay":2309101,"description":"Reigns of Louis XIII and Louis XIV. Royal power at its peak. France dominates Europe, French culture spreads. Start of large-scale sea trade.","jurisdictionLevel":3},{"id":1670188,"age":25,"year":"1618","toYear":"1648","julianDay":2312023,"title":"30 Years War","description":"Ferdinand II was trying to force the people to follow Catholicism. The 30 years war was a battle of religion with the Protestants and Catholics, in the Holy Roman Empire.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/reformation/thirty-years-war","urlTitle":"History-Thirty Years' War","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Antoinette Tarillon was born about 1593, in Schirmeck, Bas-Rhin, Alsace, France, her father, Jean Tarillon, was 22 and her mother, Mrs Catherine Marchal, was 22. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Humbert Marchal. She died about 1660, in her hometown, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1593–1660":"umbes1593–umbes1660","1590–1663":"1590–